-- Raw Sugar Declines Most Since September: Commodities at Close
-- B y   P a t r i c k   M c K i e r n a n
-- 2012-01-05T22:46:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-05/raw-sugar-declines-most-since-september-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI Spot  Index (SPGSCI) 
of 24 commodities fell 1.3 percent to close at 661.32 at 3:43
p.m. in  New York , led by sugar and wheat.  The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index (CMCIPI)  of 26 raw materials dropped
1.4 percent to 1,539.74.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Sugar fell the most since September as weather conditions
improved for  Brazil ’s cane crop, the world’s largest, and the
dollar’s rally curbed the appeal of commodities as investments.  Brazil’s Center South, the world’s top producing region,
will get rains in the next 10 days, easing concern that an
earlier dry spell would erode yields from this year’s harvest,
weather forecaster Somar Meteorologia said today.  Raw sugar for March delivery plunged 5.3 percent to 23.13
cents a pound on ICE Futures in New York, the biggest decline
since Sept. 16. The price slumped 27 percent in 2011 as crops
expanded in  Asia  and Europe.  Arabica-coffee futures for March delivery declined 3.2
percent to $2.1955 a pound in New York, the biggest drop since
Oct. 31. The price has dropped 29 percent since reaching a 14-
year high in May.  Cocoa futures for March delivery dropped 2.3 percent to
$2,028 a metric ton. Earlier, the price touched $2,016, the
lowest for a most-active contract since Dec. 12.  Orange-juice futures for March delivery fell 0.3 percent to
settle at $1.776 a pound.  Cotton futures for March delivery declined 1.2 percent to
94.74 cents a pound.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Wheat futures tumbled the most in three weeks on
speculation that rains will revive dry fields in  South America ,
boosting prospects for global grain production.  On the Chicago Board of Trade, wheat futures for March
delivery slumped 3.2 percent to $6.2925 a bushel, the biggest
decline since Dec. 14. Earlier, the price touched $6.265, the
lowest for since Dec. 23.  Corn futures for March delivery fell 2.3 percent to close
at $6.435 a bushel, the biggest drop since Dec. 14.  Soybean futures for March delivery declined 1.7 percent to
$12.09 a bushel, the biggest drop since Dec. 9.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold futures rose, capping the longest rally in 10 weeks,
after U.K. Defense Secretary Philip Hammond said the country may
take military action if  Iran  carries out its threat to block the
 Strait of Hormuz .  On the Comex in New York, gold futures for February
delivery advanced 0.5 percent to $1,620.10 an ounce. The metal
rose for the fourth straight session, the longest rally since
late October.  Silver futures for March delivery rose 0.7 percent to
$29.296 an ounce. Earlier, the price dropped as much as 1.4
percent.  On the  New York Mercantile Exchange , palladium futures for
March delivery fell 1.4 percent to $644.40 an ounce. Platinum
futures for April delivery dropped 0.6 percent to $1,418 an
ounce.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas fell to the lowest in more than two years after
a government report showed a widening U.S. surplus of the
heating and power-plant fuel.  Gas futures for February delivery fell 3.7 percent to $2.98
per million British thermal units on the Nymex, the lowest
settlement price since Sept. 11, 2009.  U.K. summer gas erased early gains, tracking  Brent crude ,
amid ample storage inventories and low demand.  U.K. summer gas fell amid ample inventories and low demand.  Summer gas for delivery in the six months from April
dropped 0.5 pence to 52.5 pence a therm at 4:30 p.m. in  London .
That’s equal to $8.13 per million Btu. A therm is 100,000 Btu.  CRUDE OIL  Crude oil fell for the first time in three days as U.S.
inventories gained and borrowing costs in  France  rose, adding to
concern that Europe will struggle to contain the debt crisis.  Oil futures for February delivery fell 1.4 percent to
$101.81 a barrel on the Nymex.  Brent oil for February settlement fell 0.8 percent to
$112.74 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures  Europe 
exchange.  Royal Dutch Plc sought to sell three cargoes of North Sea
Forties crude without success after selling two shipments
yesterday. Gunvor Group Ltd. failed to buy Russian Urals blend
in northwest Europe at a higher price.  Shell declared force majeure on Bonny Light loadings
following leaks on the Nembe Creek Trunkline caused by oil
theft.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline fell the most in three weeks as the Energy
Department reported that inventories rose to a nine-month high
and demand slid the most in 11 weeks.  Gasoline futures for February delivery fell 1.7 percent to
$2.7365 a gallon on the Nymex, ending a four-session rally.  Heating oil futures for February delivery declined 1.7
percent to $3.0388 a gallon, the biggest drop since Dec. 14.  LIVESTOCK  Hog futures fell to a two-week low on speculation that
demand for U.S. pork is slowing amid increasing supplies. Cattle
also declined, while feeder-cattle advanced to a record.  Hog futures for February settlement fell 1.6 percent to
83.85 cents a pound on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, after
reaching 83.775 cents, the lowest since Dec. 22.  Cattle futures for February delivery dropped 0.6 percent to
settle at $1.2095 a pound. Prices have rallied 13 percent in the
past 12 months.  Feeder-cattle futures for March settlement gained 0.2
percent to $1.5085 a pound, after reaching a record $1.521.
Prices are up 23 percent in the past year.  BASE METALS  Copper fell for the second straight day on concern that
Europe’s debt crisis is deepening, eroding prospects for the
economy and metal demand.  Copper futures for March delivery declined 0.2 percent to
$3.4265 a pound on the Comex. Yesterday, the metal slumped 2.7
percent, the most in three weeks, amid signs of faltering
manufacturing and service industries in Europe.  On the London Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months was unchanged at $7,540 a metric ton ($3.42 a pound).  Lead, zinc, aluminum and nickel fell in London. Tin
climbed.  To contact the reporter on this story:
